1 (b) The term does not include:
2 (i) a shared solar energy facility; or
3 (ii) a subscribing customer.
4 (4) "Shared solar energy facility" means a solar energy facility whose output is shared through
5 subscriptions and that:
6 (a) is connected to a public utility's distribution system behind a production meter that is capable of
7 recording the cumulative kilowatt hours produced by a shared solar energy facility;
8 (b) has generating capacity of not more than 5 megawatts;
9 (c) has generating capacity of not less than 50 kilowatts; and
10 (d) produces electricity for which two or more subscribing customers within the same service
11 territory receive an on-bill credit.
12 (5) "Shared solar energy facility owner" means a public utility, public-private partnership, for-profit
13 business, or nonprofit organization dedicated to operating a shared solar energy facility.
14 (6) "Subscribing customer" means a retail electricity consumer receiving an on-bill credit for
15 electric generation from a shared solar energy facility. Subscribers must be located in the same service territory
16 as the shared solar energy facility. A subscriber may not be a customer-generator as defined in 69-8-103.
17
18 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Shared solar energy requirements -- public utility. (1) A public utility
19 shall interconnect a shared solar energy facility that meets the requirements of this chapter to its distribution
20 system.
21 (2) The proportion of the shared solar energy facility's generating capacity assignable to a
22 subscribing customer must represent at least 1 kilowatt of generating capacity.
23 (3) A shared solar energy facility must be located within the service territory of the offering public
24 utility.
25 (4) A public utility shall grant an on-bill credit in accordance with rules adopted by the commission
26 to the accounts of subscribing customers.
27 (5) A shared solar energy facility owner generating electricity for subscribing customers shall
28 provide a public utility with:
